<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA72">
<l>aṉpāḻi yāṉai yaṇukeṉṉu nāvavaṉṟaṉ</l>
<l>paṇpāḻit tōḷparavi yētteṉṉu – muṉpūḻi</l>
<l>kāṇāṉaik kāṇeṉṉuṅ kaṇcevi kēḷeṉṉum</l>
<l>pūṇāram pūṇṭāṉ pukaḻ</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Love says ‘approach him with the discus’. The tongue says</l>
<l>‘laud [and] praise the arm of him with the excellent discus.’ ‘See him</l>
<l>who did not see earlier aeons<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The meaning of the phrase muṉp’ ūḻi kāṇāṉ is not obvious. The simple literal reading given above begs the question: why did god not see earlier aeons? The Vyākyānam, aware of the problem, suggests an elliptical direct object: ōr aṭi varaniṉṟāl kuṟṟamē aṉṟiyē kuṟṟam kiṭakkum nāḷum kāṇavariyāṉ, “if you take one step towards him, he will find it difficult to see not not just the offences [but] also the days you committed them”, in other words, he kindly overlooks past errances.</note>,’  says the eye. The ear says ‘listen</l>
<l>to the praises of him who wore the ornamental wreath.’</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
